\begin_layout Subsection
Reduction from Subset sum
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The subset sum problem is well known to be NP-complete.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It can be defined with the question: for a given set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}\subset\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
does there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}\subseteq\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{l_{i}\in\mathcal{L}}\;l_{i}=0$
\end_inset

?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We reduce from subset sum to Problem 1 by showing any general solution to
 Problem 1 could be used to solve subset sum with only linear time additional
 work.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}=\{w_{1},w_{2},...,w_{m}\}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
for 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega=2m\left(\max_{i\in[1,m]}\,|w_{i}|+1\right)$
\end_inset

 and thus more than two times the size of the largest possible sum of elements
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=\frac{1}{2m}\left(\min_{i\in[1,m]}\,|w_{i}|\right)$
\end_inset

 and thus smaller than any element of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
then we can define an embedding vocabulary 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We map each integer in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

